column1: What will be the approval rating for the Russian government in December 2017?
column6: ['Non-US Politics']
column11: This question will be resolved using data reported by the Levada Center. Data can be accessed here by referencing the the month of interest in the "Do you approve the activities of the Russian Government?" table. Question will be resolved when data is first released. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

column6: I am making this forecast as I believe Russian citizens will generally be satisfied with their country on an international level as there is a strong desire for Russia to project her power. Recent world events have shown that Russia has a strong influence on geopolitical events and can exert power to influence situations in her national interest. The Russian economy has recovered to some extent from international sanctions and has proven to be resilient against external forces. Russia has been able to effectively bolster the regime of Bashar Al-Assad against the wishes of Western governments. The annexation of Crimea was also a success for Russia as Western response has been weak. Russian foreign policy and military strategy is highly lateral and of an asymmetric nature. The Soviet concept of Maskirovka is highly effective. Russia is once again a great world power and the unipolar world of the post Soviet era has come to an end, with Russia, USA and China formking a troika of sorts.
Had time to look into the +10 point increase in December 2003. I'm attributing that outlier to Putin's United Russia party victory [1] and 4 consecutive years of economic growth [1, 2, 3]
The data is unreliable. Regardless, Putin maintains a strong cult of personality status in the face of any opposition.

The approval ratings for the government have been dropping gradually over the fall and winter. This might be partially due to recent events, but is probably also influenced by the upcoming elections and the usual tactics of politicians dealing with opponents. However, I don't see anything that would cause a large drop or rise in approval ratings for December.
Currently at 42%, it rarely sees a change larger than 4% but it was at 48% in October
November was only 42 (I think) and things seem to be dropping. Plus they got banned from upcoming winter Olympics.
Putin's handling of political opponents prior to election
His approval rating has been between 80-90% all year. There is no reason to think it would suddenly drop so much in a few days.
Put in is well liked in Russia
The recent trend is a downward decline, and in the past year ~17% of months have experienced a 6+ change in approval rating.
Approval rating for the Gov't of Russia by whom? The Russian people? As far as I know, the Putin-led government is generally popular with Russia's populace; this will not change any time soon.
Based on November, it should be < 48, but i believe it has a strong chance of recovering to pre-November levels.
Statistically it will remain much the same

The november rating is 42. The average rating is 45.77. The monthly diff from one month to the next is on average 2.76. The chance of a 6 point increase is 3.77% historically. And the chance of a 9 point increase is ~1% historically
The peoples of Russia are glad to know of Russia's success in Syria and the increasing influence on the world stage. They believe Putin know's what he's doing, however domestic affairs he is lacking

The number tend to fluctuate between 48 and 51, except for novermber.

Base rate looking at the last two years is 48.1% with only one occasion (09/17) more than 51. Could not find news which would explain the drop to 42 in November, but it seems unlikely to climb by so many points in one month judging from past changes in approval ratings.

This is difficult. Currently the rating is 42 and for the past ten years the six percent leap has happened approximately only once per year. A couple of those times has been around December which might or might not be a coincidence. Furthermore, the rating has been at least 48 for the past five months before November so the drop was quite substantial. Not sure if the situation with the Olympics might affect this but I think it would more affect Putin's rating.
Eyeballing the data from last months. Nov. 2017 was 42 & I didn't see big jumps in approval ratings from one month to the next --> more probability mass for "<48".

Hard to say. Every time the President of the United States does something stupid or the rest of the United States carries on as if Putin were omniscient and omnipotent, Putin's numbers go up. Stay tuned.
